Hey! That's a pretty straightforward one. The problem is that you're mixing Rust types improperly. In Rust, when you use `for elem in vec` on a `Vec<u8>`, `elem` will be an owned `u8`, not a reference or slice like in some other languages. Here's the corrected code snippet to sum a Vec<u8> efficiently: 

```rust
fn sum_vec_u8(vec: &Vec<u8>) -> u64 {
    vec.iter().map(|&x| x as u64).sum()
}
```

Good call! Zero-cost abstractions mean that the Rust compiler can optimize away unnecessary bounds checks or indirections. Here's an alternative using raw pointers for a tighter loop:

```rust
use std::slice;

crate fn sum_vec_u8_fast(vec: &Vec<u8>) -> u64 {
    let slice = vec.as_slice();
    unsafe {
        let ptr = slice.as_ptr() as *const u8;
        let len = slice.len();
        std::slice::from_raw_parts(ptr, len).iter().map(|&x| x as u64).sum()
    }
}
```

